{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T15-03-32-404Z","slug":"your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance","locale":"es","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T15:03:41.688Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-12-29--your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance/es/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/your-foreign-keys-are-killing-performance/es/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T15-03-32-404Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"710eef136b3fb20edb779995cdd3e6132250ff49ebbe95c2159902711bea426c","outputHash":"435b7b8db713bde55f67430827c60afb6f7d36c9ca77404d84f9cdb25ea38b20","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that the debate over foreign‑key performance is misplaced: constraints always incur some cost, but the real decision is which failure mode—data corruption, orphaned rows, or lost write throughput—is acceptable for a given application. Using a weather‑monitoring example, the author shows when foreign keys make sense (e.g., static reference data or critical billing integrity) and when they are wasteful (high‑volume sensor inserts where a denormalized, append‑only log is preferable). The piece frames foreign keys as safety features—like seatbelts—that add “weight” but protect against specific risks, urging developers to treat “best practices” as design patterns rather than moral rules. It targets web‑developers, DBAs, and architects who wrestle with normalization versus performance, and it adopts an analytical, slightly admonishing tone with the recurring metaphor of safety equipment versus speed.","totalInputTokens":10702,"totalOutputTokens":3154,"totalCacheReadTokens":5504,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":7880,"totalCostUsd":0.0009850979999999998,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"opena